  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">DELT4SLOG 2</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This project becomes necessary as a result of the increasing poverty in the Niger Delta region. The Niger Delta region of Nigeria  plays host to over 80% of Nigeria&apos;s entire wealth. Large deposits of oil and natural gas has ensured that the Niger Delta continues to be plundered to provide the needed foreign exchange for Nigeria. Since the inception of this present democratic regime in Nigeriain 1999, Nigeria&apos;s fortunes from crude oil sales have increased astronomically.  According to Federal Minister ofFinance, allocations to the states, federal and local government increased by over 500% from June 1999 to May 2007. So much funds, running into trillions of Naira have accrued to all tiers of Government in Nigeria. For instance, in June 1999, the 36 states shared a total of 8 billion naira and in April 2007, they shared 118 billion naira. The bulk of these allocations (between 1999 to May, 2007) came to some ofthe Niger Delta States. Akwa Ibom received N384,370,238,540.34 billion, Bayelsa N414,158,710,867.12 billion, Cross River N115,403,682,833.25 billion, Delta N463,459,893,918.76 billion, Edo N119,085,051,909.31 billion, Rivers N517,682,993,860.57 billion. The NigerDelta Development Commission (NDDC) received over N3.6 trillion from the Federation Account between the same periods. The total partnership funding and contributions from the oil companies to the NDDC was above $362 million dollars as at December, 2006.

Unfortunately, the figures above have not in any way translated to a better living condition for the people. As a result, we view the Niger Delta as a region of trillions in poverty. This has been worsened by the fact that, the growing level of insecurity has further scared potential investors which could have enhanced socio-economic development for the people. Additionally, the state of insecurity has forced citizens change agents within the region into hiding or exile leaving most communities without models, social entrepreneursor activists that would advance their course and give the voices to engage with government and oil companies to demand for corporate and public accountability.  Corruption in oil exploration has led to environmental degradation denying the host communities of notonly the proceeds of revenue but also the environment that supports traditional livelihoods such as fishing and farming.</narrative>
  </description>
  <participating-org role="4" type="90">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Niger Delta Budget Monitoring Group (NDEBUMOG)</narrative>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The Niger Delta Budget Monitoring Group, NDEBUMOG is a regional non- governmental organization formed in 2005, and works in the areas of budget advocacy, transparency, accountability and anti-corruption in the Niger Delta and Nigeria in general. It has the mission to promote transparency and accountability in the public resource management through pro-poor budgeting and anti-corruption in theNiger Delta and democratic consolidation in Nigeria. Novib and NDEBUMOG started collaborating in 2011 to support small initiative of Deepening Expenditure Line Tracking of States and LGAs within the Niger Delta focusing on mobilizing citizens and building capacity for the expenditure tracking using participatory approaches.

Following the success of the DELT4SLOG1, as reported in the 2012 Narrative report and observed by the toolbox team in March 2013, Oxfam Novib decided to support the planned DELT4SLOG 2 to deepen the achieved outcomes of the project in 2012.   The project aims to gather useful budget data for advocacy through desk review and field budget tracking of capital projects in the selected locations, strengthen the capacity of CSOs, NDEBUMOG staff, Journalists and community representatives on budget tracking, and established platforms of engagement in Rivers, Bayelsa and Delta States to hold governments accountable on its stewardship through dialogue with the Legislatures and other government representatives.</narrative>
  </participating-org>
